{"title_page": "Greg Ruckman", "text_new": "{{short description|American rower}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor      = lightblue\n| name             = Greg Ruckman\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = \n| fullname         = Gregory Michael Ruckman\n| nickname         = \n| nationality      = \n| residence        = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1973|12|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cincinnati]], Ohio, United States\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| height           = \n| weight           = \n| website          = \n| country          = United States\n| sport            = Rowing\n| event            = \n| club             = \n| team             = \n| turnedpro        = \n| coach            = \n| retired          = \n| coaching         = \n| worlds           = \n| regionals        = \n| nationals        = \n| olympics         = \n| medaltemplates   =\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Rowing Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[1999 World Rowing Championships|1999 St. Catharines]] | Lwt eight}}\n}}\n\n'''Gregory Michael Ruckman''' (born December 30, 1973) is an American rower. He competed at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] and [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in [[Athens]], where he placed 7th in the [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight double sculls|men's lightweight double sculls]], along with [[Steve Tucker (rower)|Steve Tucker]]. Ruckman was born in [[Cincinnati]], Ohio.<ref>{{Cite sports-reference|name=Greg Ruckman |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ru/greg-ruckman-1.html |accessdate=October 1, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203215410/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ru/greg-ruckman-1.html |archivedate=December 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  He graduated from [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ivyleague.com/sports/2017/7/28/history-olympics-Ivies-in-Athens-Recap-2004.aspx|title=Ivies in Athens Recap (2004)|website=ivyleague.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{World champions \u2013 Lightweight men's eight}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruckman, Greg}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson rowers]]\n\n\n{{US-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor      = lightblue\n| name             = Greg Ruckman\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = \n| fullname         = Gregory Michael Ruckman\n| nickname         = \n| nationality      = \n| residence        = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1973|12|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cincinnati]], Ohio, United States\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| height           = \n| weight           = \n| website          = \n| country          = United States\n| sport            = Rowing\n| event            = \n| club             = \n| team             = \n| turnedpro        = \n| coach            = \n| retired          = \n| coaching         = \n| worlds           = \n| regionals        = \n| nationals        = \n| olympics         = \n| medaltemplates   =\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Rowing Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[1999 World Rowing Championships|1999 St. Catharines]] | Lwt eight}}\n}}\n\n'''Gregory Michael Ruckman''' (born December 30, 1973) is an American rower. He competed at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] and [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in [[Athens]], where he placed 7th in the [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight double sculls|men's lightweight double sculls]], along with [[Steve Tucker (rower)|Steve Tucker]]. Ruckman was born in [[Cincinnati]], Ohio.<ref>{{Cite sports-reference|name=Greg Ruckman |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ru/greg-ruckman-1.html |accessdate=October 1, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203215410/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ru/greg-ruckman-1.html |archivedate=December 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  He graduated from [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ivyleague.com/sports/2017/7/28/history-olympics-Ivies-in-Athens-Recap-2004.aspx|title=Ivies in Athens Recap (2004)|website=ivyleague.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{World champions \u2013 Lightweight men's eight}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruckman, Greg}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson rowers]]\n\n\n{{US-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"American rower\", overriding Wikidata description \"American rower\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greg_Ruckman"}
{"title_page": "MinecraftOnline", "text_new": "{{Afd-merge to|Minecraft server|MinecraftOnline|23 April 2020}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = MinecraftOnline\n| logo = Logo of MCO.png\n| logo caption = The logo of MinecraftOnline, featuring a Minecraft diamond pickaxe and axe.\n| developer =\n| platform =\n| genre =\n| website = {{URL|http://minecraftonline.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''MinecraftOnline''' ('''MCO''') is the oldest running survival multiplayer [[Minecraft server]],<ref name=\"mainsite\">{{cite web |url=http://minecraftonline.com/ |title=minecraftonline.com |url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821184549/http://minecraftonline.com/| archive-date=August 21, 2010 |access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gamesradar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/minecraft-oldest-server/|title=\"Welcome to Freedonia\": Minecraft's oldest server is still a mind-boggling menagerie of marvel and wonder|first=Alex|last=Avard|date=September 27, 2017|access-date=April 17, 2020|work=[[GamesRadar+]]}}</ref><ref name=\"celebspulse\">{{cite news |last=Peng |first=Mei| url=https://celebspulse.com/4-oldest-minecraft-servers-and-why-they-matter/ |title=4 Oldest Minecraft Servers and Why They Matter |date=October 19, 2019 |access-date=April 18, 2020| website=Celebs Pulse| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"oldest\">{{cite news | url=https://www.oldest.org/entertainment/minecraft-servers/| title=7 Oldest Minecraft Servers |access-date=April 18, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> created by SlowRiot on the first day of the official [[Minecraft]] multiplayer release (Minecraft Alpha 1.0.15) and opened to the public after 2 days of testing.<ref>http://minecraftonline.com/wiki/Timeline#2010</ref> Unlike most Minecraft servers, the world map has never been reset, making it the oldest running map in the game.\n\n==Hardware==\nThe server runs on Debian Linux 7, 8x Xeon CPUs, 32GB of RAM, 8x i7-2600 3.4&nbsp;GHz. The server is located in [[Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minecraftonline.com/wiki/Hardware|title=Hardware - MinecraftOnline|website=minecraftonline.com}}</ref>\n\n==Moderation==\nEvery block players break or place is logged. Staff are notified when a block is modified. Staff also gets an alert every time a player is caught cheating.\n==History==\nThe next day the server was opened to the public, the first few players were promoted to moderators. MinecraftOnline started logging every block the player places or breaks.\n\nIn the first month 1000 unique players joined the server, the number of banned players reached 100. By January 2011 10,000 players logged in on the server at least once.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minecraftonline.com/wiki/Timeline|title=Timeline - MinecraftOnline|website=minecraftonline.com}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2011 the user by the name of Bill shields made a post on [[7chan]] claiming they were banned on the server for grief. Players started joining and griefing everything around them. The total ban counter reached 4000 players in a few days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minecraftonline.com/wiki/May_Unrest|title=May Unrest - MinecraftOnline|website=minecraftonline.com}}</ref>\n\nOn June 1, 2016 YouTuber TheCampingRusher uploaded a video covering another Minecraft server called [[2b2t]], the anarchy server with no rules. In his video, he stated that 2b2t is the oldest Minecraft server. People started to search it up and found MinecraftOnline instead. Many people started to grief thinking they were on 2b2t. The ban counter reached 18,000 players.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minecraftonline.com/wiki/Rusherpocalypse|title=Rusherpocalypse - MinecraftOnline|website=minecraftonline.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MQbnPn5BM-E|title=OLDEST SERVER IN MINECRAFT!!}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2017 Slovakian YouTuber StudioMoonTV uploaded a video of them breaking torches and getting themselves banned on this server. Since then players from Czechia or Slovakia join the server and start breaking torches on a highway from spawn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4IlJsazPu0I|title=Dostal som ban na najstar\u0161om minecraftovom serveri v dejin\u00e1ch}}</ref>\n\nOn August 9, 2018 the server was blacklisted by [[Mojang]] for violating their [[End-user license agreement]]. The donation system the server had, had to be changed to only give players cosmetics. The server was removed from Mojang's blacklist on the 20 August.\n\nOn April 4, 2020 YouTuber FitMC uploaded a video dedicated to this server. A peak of 120 players online was reached for the very first time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-BjZIzagevE|title=Minecraft's Oldest Server Was Griefed (MinecraftOnline)}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://minecraftonline.com/}}\n\n{{Minecraft}}\n\n[[Category:Minecraft servers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Afd-merge to|Minecraft server|MinecraftOnline|23 April 2020}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = MinecraftOnline\n| logo = Logo of MCO.png\n| logo caption = The logo of MinecraftOnline, featuring a diamond pickaxe and axe.\n| developer =\n| platform =\n| genre =\n| website = {{URL|http://minecraftonline.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''MinecraftOnline''' ('''MCO''') is the oldest running survival multiplayer [[Minecraft server]],<ref name=\"mainsite\">{{cite web |url=http://minecraftonline.com/ |title=minecraftonline.com |url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821184549/http://minecraftonline.com/| archive-date=August 21, 2010 |access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gamesradar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/minecraft-oldest-server/|title=\"Welcome to Freedonia\": Minecraft's oldest server is still a mind-boggling menagerie of marvel and wonder|first=Alex|last=Avard|date=September 27, 2017|access-date=April 17, 2020|work=[[GamesRadar+]]}}</ref><ref name=\"celebspulse\">{{cite news |last=Peng |first=Mei| url=https://celebspulse.com/4-oldest-minecraft-servers-and-why-they-matter/ |title=4 Oldest Minecraft Servers and Why They Matter |date=October 19, 2019 |access-date=April 18, 2020| website=Celebs Pulse| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"oldest\">{{cite news | url=https://www.oldest.org/entertainment/minecraft-servers/| title=7 Oldest Minecraft Servers |access-date=April 18, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> created by SlowRiot on the first day of the official [[Minecraft]] multiplayer release (Minecraft Alpha 1.0.15) and opened to the public after 2 days of testing.<ref>http://minecraftonline.com/wiki/Timeline#2010</ref> Unlike most Minecraft servers, the world map has never been reset, making it the oldest running map in the game.\n\n==Hardware==\nThe server runs on Debian Linux 7, 8x Xeon CPUs, 32GB of RAM, 8x i7-2600 3.4&nbsp;GHz. The server is located in [[Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minecraftonline.com/wiki/Hardware|title=Hardware - MinecraftOnline|website=minecraftonline.com}}</ref>\n\n==Moderation==\nEvery block players break or place is logged. Staff are notified when a block is modified. Staff also gets an alert every time a player is caught cheating.\n==History==\nThe next day the server was opened to the public, the first few players were promoted to moderators. MinecraftOnline started logging every block the player places or breaks.\n\nIn the first month 1000 unique players joined the server, the number of banned players reached 100. By January 2011 10,000 players logged in on the server at least once.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minecraftonline.com/wiki/Timeline|title=Timeline - MinecraftOnline|website=minecraftonline.com}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2011 the user by the name of Bill shields made a post on [[7chan]] claiming they were banned on the server for grief. Players started joining and griefing everything around them. The total ban counter reached 4000 players in a few days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minecraftonline.com/wiki/May_Unrest|title=May Unrest - MinecraftOnline|website=minecraftonline.com}}</ref>\n\nOn June 1, 2016 YouTuber TheCampingRusher uploaded a video covering another Minecraft server called [[2b2t]], the anarchy server with no rules. In his video, he stated that 2b2t is the oldest Minecraft server. People started to search it up and found MinecraftOnline instead. Many people started to grief thinking they were on 2b2t. The ban counter reached 18,000 players.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minecraftonline.com/wiki/Rusherpocalypse|title=Rusherpocalypse - MinecraftOnline|website=minecraftonline.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MQbnPn5BM-E|title=OLDEST SERVER IN MINECRAFT!!}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2017 Slovakian YouTuber StudioMoonTV uploaded a video of them breaking torches and getting themselves banned on this server. Since then players from Czechia or Slovakia join the server and start breaking torches on a highway from spawn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4IlJsazPu0I|title=Dostal som ban na najstar\u0161om minecraftovom serveri v dejin\u00e1ch}}</ref>\n\nOn August 9, 2018 the server was blacklisted by [[Mojang]] for violating their [[End-user license agreement]]. The donation system the server had, had to be changed to only give players cosmetics. The server was removed from Mojang's blacklist on the 20 August.\n\nOn April 4, 2020 YouTuber FitMC uploaded a video dedicated to this server. A peak of 120 players online was reached for the very first time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-BjZIzagevE|title=Minecraft's Oldest Server Was Griefed (MinecraftOnline)}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://minecraftonline.com/}}\n\n{{Minecraft}}\n\n[[Category:Minecraft servers]]\n", "name_user": "JoeballTheUseless", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MinecraftOnline"}
{"title_page": "Jordan Smith (rower)", "text_new": "{{short description|American rower, rowing coach, and teacher}}\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n'''Jordan Smith''' (born August 31, 1979) is an [[United States|American]] rower, rowing coach, and teacher.\n\nSmith was born in 1979.<ref name=\"FISA profile\">{{cite web |title= Jordan Smith |url= http://www.worldrowing.com/athletes/athlete/23939/smith-jordan |publisher=[[International Rowing Federation]] |accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref> He was a member of the US national rowing team, competing at the [[2005 World Rowing Championships]]. Jordan Smith graduated from [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://smartech.gatech.edu/jspui/bitstream/1853/11665/1/CEE_Summer06_nwsltr.pdf |title=Jordan Smith Engineers His Passion for Rowing |publisher=Georgia Tech School of Civil and Environmental Engineering |date=Summer 2006 |accessdate=July 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315134543/http://smartech.gatech.edu/jspui/bitstream/1853/11665/1/CEE_Summer06_nwsltr.pdf |archivedate=March 15, 2012 }}</ref> He is currently the Women's Head Coach for the [[Atlanta Junior Rowing Association]] in [[Roswell, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajracrew.com/team/coaches/varsity-women/|title=Varsity Women|publisher=AJRACrew|accessdate=December 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225052544/http://www.ajracrew.com/team/coaches/varsity-women/|archive-date=February 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe used to be the head coach for the rowing team at [[Emory University]] in [[Atlanta]], Georgia. While he is not rowing or coaching, he teaches science classes including [[AP Physics]] at [[Johns Creek High School]] and won teacher of the month at [[Johns Creek High School]] in 2016 and teacher of the year in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usrowing.org/pressbox/historicalresults/internationalresults/2005worldresults|title=2005 World Championships|publisher=[[USRowing]]|accessdate=June 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAs of August 2019, he is now a retired rowing coach and now one of the coaches for the Johns Creek Cross Country Team while still being a teacher at [[Johns Creek High School]]. \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Jordan (Teacher Rower)}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:American male rowers]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets rowers]]\n[[Category:Emory Eagles rowing coaches]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n'''Jordan Smith''' (born August 31, 1979) is an [[United States|American]] rower, rowing coach, and teacher.\n\nSmith was born in 1979.<ref name=\"FISA profile\">{{cite web |title= Jordan Smith |url= http://www.worldrowing.com/athletes/athlete/23939/smith-jordan |publisher=[[International Rowing Federation]] |accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref> He was a member of the US national rowing team, competing at the [[2005 World Rowing Championships]]. Jordan Smith graduated from [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://smartech.gatech.edu/jspui/bitstream/1853/11665/1/CEE_Summer06_nwsltr.pdf |title=Jordan Smith Engineers His Passion for Rowing |publisher=Georgia Tech School of Civil and Environmental Engineering |date=Summer 2006 |accessdate=July 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315134543/http://smartech.gatech.edu/jspui/bitstream/1853/11665/1/CEE_Summer06_nwsltr.pdf |archivedate=March 15, 2012 }}</ref> He is currently the Women's Head Coach for the [[Atlanta Junior Rowing Association]] in [[Roswell, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajracrew.com/team/coaches/varsity-women/|title=Varsity Women|publisher=AJRACrew|accessdate=December 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225052544/http://www.ajracrew.com/team/coaches/varsity-women/|archive-date=February 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe used to be the head coach for the rowing team at [[Emory University]] in [[Atlanta]], Georgia. While he is not rowing or coaching, he teaches science classes including [[AP Physics]] at [[Johns Creek High School]] and won teacher of the month at [[Johns Creek High School]] in 2016 and teacher of the year in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usrowing.org/pressbox/historicalresults/internationalresults/2005worldresults|title=2005 World Championships|publisher=[[USRowing]]|accessdate=June 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAs of August 2019, he is now a retired rowing coach and now one of the coaches for the Johns Creek Cross Country Team while still being a teacher at [[Johns Creek High School]]. \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Jordan (Teacher Rower)}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:American male rowers]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets rowers]]\n[[Category:Emory Eagles rowing coaches]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"American rower, rowing coach, and teacher\", overriding Wikidata description \"American rower and rowing coach\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jordan_Smith_(rower)"}
